.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.SECOND" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.second \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.second
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]second\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns an integer from 0 to
59 representing the second component of this time.
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]second\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
Use the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method to create a new
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object with the desired new value.
.PP
For general information and more examples, see
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime.prototype.second\f[R].
.PP
For \f[CR]ZonedDateTime\f[R], \f[CR]second\f[R] can be non\-continuous
due to offset changes.
While much rarer than \f[CR]hour\f[R] or \f[CR]minute\f[R] changes
(because daylight saving time shifts are usually by whole hours), it can
still happen.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using second
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56.123456789\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.second); \f[I]// 56\f[R]
.EE
.SS Non\-continuous second
Typically, \f[CR]second\f[R] always goes from 0 to 59 and then back to
0, even when passing through a daylight saving time transition.
There\(cqs a peculiar case where the second can be non\-continuous: the
standardization of hourly time zones.
In the early 20th century, most countries were using their own time
zones which were often not a whole hour offset from UTC.
For example, Paris used to have an offset of UTC+0:09:21, which was
changed to UTC+0 on March 11, 1911.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq1911\-03\-10T23:59:59+00:09:21[Europe/Paris]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.second); \f[I]// 59\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = dt.add({ seconds: 1 });
console.log(dt2.second); \f[I]// 39\f[R]
console.log(dt2.toString()); \f[I]// 1911\-03\-10T23:50:39+00:00[Europe/Paris]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For this reason, you should always prefer \f[CR]add()\f[R] and
\f[CR]subtract()\f[R] to manipulate dates and times, rather than
directly changing the \f[CR]second\f[R] property.
